This gives \(41\) pairs (since there are 41 integers from \(-20\) to \(20\)). 2. **Case 2: \(b \neq c\)** - If the quadratics share a common root \(\alpha\), then \(\alpha\) must satisfy both equations. Subtracting the equations gives \((b - c)(\alpha - 1) = 0\). Since \(b \neq c\), we must have \(\alpha = 1\). - Substituting \(\alpha = 1\) into both equations gives \(1 + b + c = 0\), leading to \(b + c = -1\). - We need to count the integer solutions \((b, c)\) to \(b + c = -1\) where \(b \neq c\) and both \(b\) and \(c\) are within the range \(-20\) to \(20\). - For each \(b\) from \(-20\) to \(19\) (inclusive), \(c = -1 - b\) must also be within the range \(-20\) to \(20\). This results in \(40\) valid pairs (since \(b\) ranges from \(-20\) to \(19\), inclusive, giving 40 values). Summing the results from both cases, we get: - \(41\) pairs from Case 1 (where \(b = c\)) - \(40\) pairs from Case 2 (where \(b \neq c\) and \(b + c = -1\)) Thus, the total number of ordered pairs \((b, c)\) is \(41 + 40 = 81\). \[ \boxed{81} \]
